LICENSE-AGPL, and online at https://www.gnu.org/licenses/agpl-3.0.html.

What this means in practice for the typical end user:

  * Running the official Kaption installer (or building Kaption from this
    source) for your own personal use imposes NO obligations on you.
    You do not need to publish anything. Just running the binary is not
    "distributing" the software.

  * If you redistribute Kaption — for example, you fork the repository,
    modify it, and ship a binary or installer to other people — the
    AGPL-3.0 obligations apply: you must release your full modified
    source code under AGPL-3.0, and you must preserve copyright and
    licence notices.

  * If you bundle Kaption code (or substantial portions of it) into a
    larger product, that product must also be released under AGPL-3.0.

  * The AGPL "network use" clause (Section 13) does not normally apply
    to Kaption, because Kaption is a desktop client, not a hosted
    service. If you build a network service that exposes Kaption to
    remote users, Section 13 applies and you must offer those users
    the source.

